name: ‚ôª reposting 7 Reasons why I Don‚Äôt Write

photo.alt: User Avatar of J L Gatewood

summary.html:
I have recently been made aware that the frequency of new content published on my site has gone down quite a bit.

Ok fine, I trash-talked Manuel‚Äôs website on Mastodon and he correctly pointed out that while I wrote an impressive two (2) blogposts last year, he wrote around 90 (while also doing talks, audits, raising an infant daughter and probably training for a marathon or some shit like that, I mean let‚Äôs face it the guy is annoyingly productive).

I know I was slacking off a bit and those numbers speak for themselves. While I generally want to write, ideas rarely make it all the way to a published post.

Like many others, ‚Äúwrite more‚Äù is high up on my imaginary list of life improvements and although I don‚Äôt usually do new year‚Äôs resolutions, now feels like a good time to re-evaluate what‚Äôs stopping me there.

I came up with seven reasons that I use to justify why I‚Äôm not writing. In a confusing twist of perspective, I‚Äôm also going to try and talk myself out of them by explaining to you, dear Reader, why they are bullshit.

I don‚Äôt have time
This is the big one, right? We all have other things to do, and writing takes time. In my case, I‚Äôve been really swamped with client projects and other work last year.

I don‚Äôt have anything interesting to say
The classic impostor syndrome comes out here. I don‚Äôt know anything special, so why bother?

I gotta fix [X] on my site first
This one is especially popular among developers. ‚ÄúHow can I possibly write anything before the typography is perfect? How can I ever publish anything when comments are not implemented yet?‚Äù

Others have already written about this
Sometimes I‚Äôve got a great idea for a post, but an initial Google search reveals that someone else already beat me to it.

The moment for this has passed
There are writing ideas that are inspired by some event or conversation.

I can‚Äôt get it to sound right
Most of the (tech) blogs I read are in English, even though its authors are from all over the world.

Nobody‚Äôs going to read it anyway
Let‚Äôs be honest: nobody likes to shout into the void. Everyone wants their content to be seen, and social validation is the sweet sweet dopamine reward we all crave.

content.html:
I feel somehow singled-out.

ü§£

This is a great read and good reminder to JUST WRITE for the hell of it, and don‚Äôt worry about formatting, audience and sometimes even subject. Just write if YOU think the topic is interesting enough; others who need it see it will hear it. And hey, at some point amongst those lead stones that are constantly being churned out, will be some diamonds!
